Rating: 0
Omigosh, Yum! I tried this recipe, because corn is in season, and I had five fresh cobs. I changed a few things: because I didn't use bacon, I added/sauteed 1/2 diced onion, 1 minced celery, and a few ounces of shelled lobster. I also added a small amount of cayenne, and a dollop of white wine! My grocery store didn't have fresh clams, so I used several cans of whole clams. I served in heated sourdough bowls, with a small piece of lobster on top! I'm not usually this fancy, but Wow!

Rating: 3
This was tasty and easy to make. I did use frozen corn as well as mini new potatoes (that needed dicing but not peeling), which cut the labor a bit. Added about 1/2 tsp. dried thyme leaves, a similar quantity of dried chiles, and some minced parsley at the end. I used 2% milk and creamo (10%) rather than the called for homo milk and heavy cream (had them left over from a brunch) and result was fine. A wonderful Friday night meal with some crusty bread.

Rating: 4
This chowder is worth digging your own clams for. Great as written but awesome with a few extra clams.

Rating: 4
Great recipe. I only changed it a bit. I added extra piece of bacon and once it was slightly browned added a half of red bell pepper diced small. I did not add the corn (used frozen) with the potato as others had advised. I also only used aprox 3/4 lb potato. Once the clams opened up i added the corn. I did take all the clams out of the shells (didn't take too long). I like my soup a bit thicker so i added some corn starch to white wine and added that. The white wine (sav blanc) added another layer which was really great! I did a a bit of red pepper flakes per other reviews. Soup was yummy! Served with sliced toasted baguette that I broiled with a bit of olive oil.

Rating: 4
I have made this three times. I don't make any changes, except I halve it because there are only two of us. Plus, two bottles of clam juice is sorta expensive. (Another reviewer uses fish stock-may be less expensive.) But, this is DELICIOUS! I am going to make it Friday with frozen corn from last summer. :)

